# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pneumatic-cylinder
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] 3D computer graphics, contrary to what the name suggests, are most often displayed on two-dimensional displays.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Unlike 3D film and similar techniques, the result is two-dimensional, without visual depth.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] More often, 3D graphics are being displayed on 3D displays, like in virtual reality systems.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] 3D graphics stand in contrast to 2D computer graphics which typically use completely different methods and formats for creation and rendering.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] 3D computer graphics rely on many of the same algorithms as 2D computer vector graphics in the wire-frame model and 2D computer raster graphics in the final rendered display.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] In computer graphics software, 2D applications may use 3D techniques to achieve effects such as lighting, and similarly, 3D may use some 2D rendering techniques.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] The objects in 3D computer graphics are often referred to as 3D models.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Unlike the rendered image, a model's data is contained within a graphical data file.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] A 3D model is a mathematical representation of *any* three-dimensional object; a model is not technically a *graphic* until it is displayed.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] A model can be displayed visually as a two-dimensional image through a process called 3D rendering, or it can be used in non-graphical computer simulations and calculations.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] With 3D printing, models are rendered into an actual 3D physical representation of themselves, with some limitations as to how accurately the physical model can match the virtual model.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] William Fetter was credited with coining the term *computer graphics* in 1961 to describe his work at Boeing.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] An early example of interactive 3-D computer graphics was explored in 1963 by the Sketchpad program at Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Lincoln Laboratory.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] One of the first displays of computer animation was *Futureworld* (1976), which included an animation of a human face and a hand that had originally appeared in the 1972 experimental short *A Computer Animated Hand*, created by University of Utah students Edwin Catmull and Fred Parke.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D computer graphics software began appearing for home computers in the late 1970s.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] The earliest known example is *3D Art Graphics*, a set of 3-D computer graphics effects, written by Kazumasa Mitazawa and released in June 1978 for the Apple II.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Virtual Reality 3D is a version of 3D computer graphics.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Although the first VR headsets appeared in the late 1950s, VR did not become widely popular until the 2000s.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] In 2012 the Oculus was released and since then, the 3D VR headset world has expanded.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] The modeling describes the process of forming the shape of an object.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] The two most common sources of 3D models are those that an artist or engineer originates on a computer with a 3D modeling tool, or models scanned into a computer from real-world objects (polygonal modeling, patch modeling, and NURBS modeling are some popular tools used in 3D modeling).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Models can also be produced procedurally or via physical simulation.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Basically, a 3D model is formed from points called vertices that define the shape and form polygons.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] A polygon is an area formed from at least three vertices (a triangle).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] The overall integrity of the model and its suitability to use in animation depend on the structure of the polygons.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Before rendering into an image, objects must be laid out in a 3D scene.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] This defines spatial relationships between objects, including location and size.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Animation refers to the temporal description of an object (i.e., how it moves and deforms over time).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Popular methods include keyframing, inverse kinematics, and motion-capture).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] These techniques are often used in combination.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] As with animation, physical simulation also specifies motion.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Stop Motion has multiple categories within such as Claymation, Cutout, Silhouette, Lego, Puppets, and Pixelation.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Claymation is the use of models made of clay used for an animation.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Some examples are Clay Fighter and Clay Jam.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Lego animation is one of the more common types of stop motion.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Lego stop motion is the use of the figures themselves moving around.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Some examples of this are Lego Island and Lego Harry Potter.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Rendering converts a model into an image either by simulating light transport to get photo-realistic images, or by applying an art style as in non-photorealistic rendering.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] The two basic operations in realistic rendering are transport (how much light gets from one place to another) and scattering (how surfaces interact with light).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] This step is usually performed using 3-D computer graphics software or a 3-D graphics API.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Altering the scene into a suitable form for rendering also involves 3D projection, which displays a three-dimensional image in two dimensions.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Materials and textures are properties that the render engine uses to render the model.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] One can give the model materials to tell the render engine how to treat light when it hits the surface.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Textures are used to give the material color using a color or albedo map, or give the surface features using a bump map or normal map.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] It can also be used to deform the model itself using a displacement map.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D computer graphics software produces computer-generated imagery (CGI) through 3D modeling and 3D rendering or produces 3-D models for analytical, scientific, entertainment, and industrial purposes.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] There are many varieties of files supporting 3-D graphics, for example, Blender (.blend), Wavefront (.obj), .fbx and .x DirectX files.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Each file type generally tends to have its own unique data structure.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Each file format can be accessed through its respective applications, such as DirectX files, and Quake.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Alternatively, files can be accessed through third-party standalone programs, or via manual decompilation.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D modeling software is a class of 3-D computer graphics software used to produce 3-D models.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Individual programs of this class are called modeling applications or modelers.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D modeling starts by describing 3 display models: drawing points, drawing lines and drawing triangles and other polygonal patches.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D modelers allow users to create and alter models via their 3-D mesh.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Users can add, subtract, stretch and otherwise change the mesh to their desire.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Models can be viewed from a variety of angles, usually simultaneously.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Models can be rotated and the view can be zoomed in and out.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D modelers can export their models to files, which can then be imported into other applications as long as the metadata are compatible.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Many modelers allow importers and exporters to be plugged-in, so they can read and write data in the native formats of other applications.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Most 3-D modelers contain a number of related features, such as ray tracers and other rendering alternatives and texture mapping facilities.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Some also contain features that support or allow animation of models.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Some may be able to generate full-motion video of a series of rendered scenes (i.e. animation).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Computer-aided design software may employ the same fundamental 3-D modeling techniques that 3-D modeling software uses but their goal differs.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] They are used in computer-aided engineering, computer-aided manufacturing, Finite element analysis, product lifecycle management, 3D printing and computer-aided architectural design.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] After producing a video, studios then edit or composite the video using programs such as Adobe Premiere Pro or Final Cut Pro at the mid-level, or Autodesk Combustion, Digital Fusion, Shake at the high-end.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Match moving software is commonly used to match live video with computer-generated video, keeping the two in sync as the camera moves.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Use of real-time computer graphics engines to create a cinematic production is called machinima.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Not all computer graphics that appear 3D are based on a wireframe model.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics with 3D photorealistic effects are often achieved without wire-frame modeling and are sometimes indistinguishable in the final form.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Some graphic art software includes filters that can be applied to 2D vector graphics or 2D raster graphics on transparent layers.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Visual artists may also copy or visualize 3D effects and manually render photo-realistic effects without the use of filters.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Some video games use 2.5D graphics, involving restricted projections of three-dimensional environments, such as isometric graphics or virtual cameras with fixed angles, either as a way to improve performance of the game engine or for stylistic and gameplay concerns.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] By contrast, games using 3D computer graphics without such restrictions are said to use true 3D.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Cutout is the use of flat materials such as paper.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Everything is cut out of paper including the environment, characters, and even some props.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Silhouette is similar to cutouts except they are one solid color, black.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Puppets are dolls and different puppets used in the game.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] An example of this would be Yoshi's Wooly World.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] Pixelation is when the entire game appears pixelated, this includes the characters and the environment around them.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/3d-computer-graphics] One example of this is seen in Shovel Knight.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] An **air compressor** is a machine that takes ambient air from the surroundings and discharges it at a higher pressure.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] It is an application of a gas compressor and a pneumatic device that converts mechanical power (from an electric motor, diesel or gasoline engine, etc.) into potential energy stored in compressed air, which has many uses.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] A common application is to compress air into a storage tank, for immediate or later use.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] When the delivery pressure reaches its set upper limit, the compressor is shut off, or the excess air is released through an overpressure valve.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] The compressed air is stored in the tank until it is needed.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] The pressure energy provided by the compressed air can be used for a variety of applications such as pneumatic tools as it is released.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] When tank pressure reaches its lower limit, the air compressor turns on again and re-pressurizes the tank.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] A compressor is different from a pump because it works on a gas, while pumps work on a liquid.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] There are numerous methods of air compression, divided into either positive-displacement or roto-dynamic types.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] Positive-displacement compressors work by forcing air through a chamber whose volume is decreased to compress the air.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] Once the pressure is greater than the pressure outside the discharge valve, a port or valve opens and air is discharged into the outlet system from the compression chamber.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] The capacities for both single-stage and two-stage compressors are generally specified in Standard Cubic feet per Minute (SCFM) or litres per minute and pounds per square Inch (PSI) or bar.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] To a lesser extent, some compressors are rated in actual cubic feet per minute (ACFM).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] Still others are rated in cubic feet per minute (CFM).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] Using CFM alone to rate a compressor is ambiguous because it represents a flow rate without a pressure reference. i.e.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] Single stage compressors usually fall into the fractional through 5 horsepower range.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] Two-stage compressors normally fall into the 5 through 30 horsepower range.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] Roto-dynamic air compressors include centrifugal compressors where Rotating vanes impart kinetic energy to a gas and stationary passages convert velocity into a rise in pressure, and axial compressors, where rotor blades impart the kinetic energy and stator blades convert it to a rise in pressure.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] Due to adiabatic heating, air compressors require some method of disposing of waste heat.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] Generally this is some form of air- or water-cooling, although some (particularly rotary type) compressors may be cooled by oil (that is then in turn air- or water-cooled).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] The atmospheric changes are also considered during cooling of compressors.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] The type of cooling is determined by considering the factors such as inlet temperature, ambient temperature, power of the compressor and area of application.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] There is no single type of compressor that could be used for any application.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] Air compressors are also widely used in oil and gas, mining and drilling applications as the flushing medium, aerating muds in underbalanced drilling and in air pigging of pipelines.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] Most air compressors either are reciprocating piston type, rotary vane or rotary screw.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] Centrifugal compressors are common in very large applications, while rotary screw, scroll, and reciprocating air compressors are favoured for small and medium-sized applications.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] Air compressors are designed to utilize a variety of power sources.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] While direct drive gasoline or diesel-engines and electric motors are among the most popular, air compressors that utilize vehicle engines, power-take-off, or hydraulic ports are also commonly used in mobile applications.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] The power of a compressor is measured in HP (horsepower) and CFM (cubic feet per minute of intake air).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] The volume of the pressure vessel and the stored pressure indicate the volume of compressed air (in reserve) available.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] Gasoline and diesel-powered compressors are widely used in remote areas with problematic access to electricity.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] They are noisy and require ventilation for exhaust gases, particularly if the compressed air is to be used for a breathing air supply.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] Electric-powered compressors are widely used in production, workshops and garages with permanent access to electricity.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] Common workshop/garage compressors are 110-120 Volt or 230-240 Volt.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] Compressor tank shapes are: "pancake", "twin tank", "horizontal", and "vertical".
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] Depending on a size and purpose compressors can be stationary or portable.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] To ensure all compressor types run efficiently with no leaks, it is necessary to perform routine maintenance.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] The cost of maintenance only accounts for 8% of the life cycle cost of owning an air compressor.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] According to CAGI air compressor performance verification data sheets, the higher the isentropic efficiency is, the better the energy saving is.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] The better air compressor isentropic efficiency has reached 95%.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/air-compressor] Approximately 70~80% of the air compressor's total lifetime cost is energy consumption, so using the high-efficiency air compressor is one of the energy-saving methods.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] An **aircraft carrier** is a warship designed to carry, launch, recover and support aircraft at sea, equipped with a full-length flight deck and hangar facilities that allow it to serve as a mobile, seagoing airbase.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Typically it is the capital ship of a fleet (known as a carrier battle group), as it allows a naval force to project seaborne air power far from national territory without depending on local airfields for the staging of aircraft operations.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] While heavier fixed-wing aircraft such as airlifters, gunships and bombers have been launched from aircraft carriers, these aircraft do not often land on a carrier due to flight deck limitations.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The aircraft carrier, along with its onboard aircraft and defensive ancillary weapons, is the largest weapon system ever created.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] By their tactical prowess, mobility, autonomy and the variety of operational means, aircraft carriers are often the centerpiece of modern naval warfare, and have significant diplomatic influence in deterrence, command of the sea and air supremacy.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since the Second World War, the aircraft carrier has replaced the battleship in the role of flagship of a fleet, and largely transformed naval battles from gunfire to beyond-visual-range air strikes.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Modern navies use several variants of the aircraft carrier, sometimes categorized as sub-types of aircraft carriers and sometimes as distinct types of aviation-capable ships.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Aircraft carriers may be classified according to the type of aircraft they carry and their operational assignments.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Navies have a variety of classification systems for their ships, and a definitive number of current aircraft carriers depends on the specific criteria.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] As of July 2026 there are 9 navies operating 24 active vessels designated by their respective navies as either an "Aircraft Carrier" or "Aircraft Cruiser".
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] These range in tonnage from the United States' 100,000 tonne USS *Gerald R.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Ford* to Brazil's 21,000 tonne NAM *Atlantico*.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Some of the types listed here are not strictly defined as aircraft carriers by some sources.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] A fleet carrier is intended to operate with the main fleet and usually provides an offensive capability.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] These are the largest carriers capable of fast speeds.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] By comparison, escort carriers were developed to provide defense for convoys of ships.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] They were smaller and slower with lower numbers of aircraft carried.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Most were built from mercantile hulls or, in the case of merchant aircraft carriers, were bulk cargo ships with a flight deck added on top.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Light aircraft carriers were fast enough to operate with the main fleet but of smaller size with reduced aircraft capacity.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The Soviet aircraft carrier *Admiral Kusnetsov* was termed a "heavy aircraft-carrying cruiser".
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] This was primarily a legal construct to avoid the limitations of the Montreux Convention preventing 'aircraft carriers' transiting the Turkish Straits between the Soviet Black Sea bases and the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] These ships, while sized in the range of large fleet carriers, were designed to deploy alone or with escorts.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] In addition to supporting fighter aircraft and helicopters, they provide both strong defensive weaponry and heavy offensive missiles equivalent to a guided-missile cruiser.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The appellation "supercarrier" is not an official designation with any national navy, but a term used predominantly by the media and typically when reporting on larger and more advanced carrier types.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] It is also used when comparing carriers of various sizes and capabilities, both current and past.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] It was first used by *The New York Times* in 1938, in an article about the Royal Navy's HMS *Ark Royal*, that had a length of 800 feet (244 m), a displacement of 22,000 tons and was designed to carry 72 aircraft.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since then, aircraft carriers have consistently grown in size, both in length and displacement, as well as improved capabilities; in defense, sensors, electronic warfare, propulsion, range, launch and recovery systems, number and types of aircraft carried and number of sorties flown per day.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first aircraft carrier over 80,000 tonnes full-load displacement was the USS Forrestal launched in 1954.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] In total, the US Navy has had 5 different classes of aircraft carrier of this size definition, the Forrestal class, Kitty Hawk class, the Enterprise class, the Nimitz class and Gerald R Ford Class, two of which were conventional steam-powered and three nuclear-powered.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] USS *Enterprise*, launched in 1960, was the first carrier over 90,000 tonnes full load displacement and *Nimitz*, launched in 1972, was the first over 100,000 tonnes displacement.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] A total of 22 supercarriers have been launched by the US Navy since 1954, with 11 currently in service.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Both China (Type 003) and the United Kingdom (Queen Elizabeth class) have carriers in service with displacements from 80,000 to 85,000 tonnes and lengths from 280 to 320 meters (920 to 1,050 ft) which are described as "supercarriers".
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] France is also developing a new aircraft carrier (PANG) which is to have a full load displacement of 80,000 tonnes and will be considered a supercarrier.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The largest supercarrier in service as of 2024 is the US Navy's USS Gerald R.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Ford, with full load displacement of around 100,000 tons, length of 337 meters (1,106 ft) and capabilities that exceed those of any other class.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] A US Navy proposal for an aircraft carrier concept with a length of 1,310 feet and a displacement of 500,000 tons full load at a cost of $828 million in 1976 dollars.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Project Habakkuk could be considered an early proposal for an "ultracarrier".
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Several systems of identification symbol for aircraft carriers and related types of ship have been used.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] These include the pennant numbers used by the Royal Navy, Commonwealth countries, and Europe, along with the hull classification symbols used by the US and Canada.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Two months later, on 18 January 1911, Ely landed his Curtiss Pusher airplane on a platform on the armored cruiser USS *Pennsylvania* anchored in San Francisco Bay.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Seaplane tender support ships came next, with the French *Foudre* of 1911.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Early in World War I, the Imperial Japanese Navy ship *Wakamiya* conducted the world's first carrier-launched air raid: on 6 September 1914, the *Wakamiya* used its crane to lower Farman seaplanes into the water.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The *Wakamiya* attacked the Austro-Hungarian cruiser SMS *Kaiserin Elisabeth* and the Imperial German gunboat *Jaguar* in Jiaozhou Bay off Qingdao; neither was hit.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first attack using an air-launched torpedo occurred on 2 August, when a torpedo was fired by Flight Commander Charles Edmonds from a Short Type 184 seaplane, launched from the seaplane carrier HMS *Ben-my-Chree*.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first carrier-launched airstrike was the Tondern raid in July 1918.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Seven Sopwith Camels were launched from the battlecruiser HMS *Furious*, which had been completed as a carrier by replacing her planned forward turret with a flight deck and hangar prior to commissioning.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The Camels attacked and damaged the German airbase at Tondern, Germany (modern day Tønder, Denmark), and destroyed two zeppelin airships.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first landing of an airplane on a moving ship was by Squadron Commander Edwin Harris Dunning, when he landed his Sopwith Pup on HMS *Furious* in Scapa Flow, Orkney, on 2 August 1917.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Landing on the forward flight deck required the pilot to approach round the ship's superstructure, a difficult and dangerous manoeuver, and Dunning was later killed when his airplane was thrown overboard while attempting another landing on *Furious*.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] HMS *Furious* was modified again when her rear turret was removed and another flight deck added over a second hangar for landing aircraft over the stern.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Her funnel and superstructure remained intact, however, and turbulence from the funnel and superstructure was severe enough that only three landing attempts were successful before further attempts were forbidden.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] This experience prompted the development of vessels with a flush deck and produced the first large fleet ships.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] In 1918, HMS *Argus* became the world's first carrier capable of launching and recovering naval aircraft.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] As a result of the Washington Naval Treaty of 1922, which limited the construction of new heavy surface combat ships, most early aircraft carriers were conversions of ships that were laid down (or had served) as different ship types: cargo ships, cruisers, battlecruisers, or battleships.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] These conversions gave rise to the USS *Langley* in 1922, the US *Lexington*-class aircraft carriers (1927), Japanese *Akagi* and *Kaga*, and British *Courageous* class (of which *Furious* was one).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Specialist carrier evolution was well underway, with several navies ordering and building warships that were purposefully designed to function as aircraft carriers by the mid-1920s.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] This resulted in the commissioning of ships such as the Japanese *Hōshō* (1922), HMS *Hermes* (1924, although laid down in 1918 before *Hōshō*), and *Béarn* (1927).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] During World War II, these ships would become known as fleet carriers.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The aircraft carrier dramatically changed naval warfare in World War II, because air power was becoming a significant factor in warfare.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The advent of aircraft as focal weapons was driven by the superior range, flexibility, and effectiveness of carrier-launched aircraft.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] They had greater range and precision than naval guns, making them highly effective.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The versatility of the carrier was demonstrated in November 1940, when HMS *Illustrious* launched a long-range strike on the Italian fleet at their base in Taranto, signalling the beginning of the effective and highly mobile aircraft strikes.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] This operation in the shallow water harbor incapacitated three of the six anchored battleships at a cost of two torpedo bombers.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] World War II in the Pacific Ocean involved clashes between aircraft carrier fleets.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The Japanese surprise attack on the American Pacific fleet at Pearl Harbor naval and air bases on Sunday, 7 December 1941, was a clear illustration of the power projection capability afforded by a large force of modern carriers.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Concentrating six carriers in a single unit turned naval history about, as no other nation had fielded anything comparable.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] In the "Doolittle Raid", on 18 April 1942, the US Navy carrier USS *Hornet* sailed to within 650 nautical miles (1,200 km) of Japan and launched 16 B-25 Mitchell medium bombers from her deck in a demonstrative retaliatory strike on the mainland, including the capital, Tokyo.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] However, the vulnerability of carriers compared to traditional capital ships was illustrated by the sinking of HMS *Glorious* by German battleships during the Norwegian campaign in 1940.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] This new-found importance of naval aviation forced nations to create a number of carriers, in efforts to provide air superiority cover for every major fleet to ward off enemy aircraft.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] This extensive usage led to the development and construction of 'light' carriers.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Escort aircraft carriers, such as USS *Bogue*, were sometimes purpose-built but most were converted from merchant ships as a stop-gap measure to provide anti-submarine air support for convoys and amphibious invasions.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Following this concept, light aircraft carriers built by the US, such as USS *Independence* (commissioned in 1943), represented a larger, more "militarized" version of the escort carrier.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Although with similar complement to escort carriers, they had the advantage of speed from their converted cruiser hulls.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The UK 1942 Design Light Fleet Carrier was designed for building quickly by civilian shipyards and with an expected service life of about 3 years.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] They served the Royal Navy during the war, and the hull design was chosen for nearly all aircraft carrier equipped navies after the war, until the 1980s.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Emergencies also spurred the creation or conversion of highly unconventional aircraft carriers.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] CAM ships were cargo-carrying merchant ships that could launch (but not retrieve) a single fighter aircraft from a catapult to defend the convoy from long range land-based German aircraft.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Noteworthy converted carriers were also USS *Sable* (IX-81) and USS *Wolverine* (IX-64) that both operated on the Great Lakes for training duties and were converted from paddle steamers, making them the only aircraft carriers with this type of propulsion.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Before World War II, international naval treaties of 1922, 1930, and 1936 limited the size of capital ships, including carriers.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since World War II, aircraft carrier designs have increased in size to accommodate a steady increase in aircraft size.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The large, modern *Nimitz* class of US Navy carriers has a displacement nearly four times that of the World War II–era USS *Enterprise*, yet its complement of aircraft is roughly the same—a consequence of the steadily increasing size and weight of individual military aircraft over the years.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Today's aircraft carriers are so expensive that some nations which operate them risk significant economic and military impact if a carrier is lost.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Modern navies that operate such aircraft carriers treat them as capital ships of fleets, a role previously held by the galleons, ships-of-the-line and battleships.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] This change took place during World War II in response to air power becoming a significant factor in warfare, driven by the superior range, flexibility and effectiveness of carrier-launched aircraft.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Following the war, carrier operations continued to increase in size and importance, and along with, carrier designs also increased in size and ability.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Some of these larger carriers, dubbed by the media as "supercarriers", displacing 75,000 tons or greater, have become the pinnacle of carrier development.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Some are powered by nuclear reactors and form the core of a fleet designed to operate far from home.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Amphibious assault ships, such as the *Wasp* and *Mistral* classes, serve the purpose of carrying and landing Marines, and operate a large contingent of helicopters for that purpose.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Also known as "commando carriers" or "helicopter carriers", many have the capability to operate VSTOL aircraft.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The threatening role of aircraft carriers has a place in modern asymmetric warfare, like the gunboat diplomacy of the past.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carriers also facilitate quick and precise projections of overwhelming military power into such local and regional conflicts.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Lacking the firepower of other warships, carriers by themselves are considered vulnerable to attack by other ships, aircraft, submarines, or missiles.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The resulting group of ships is often termed a carrier strike group, battle group, carrier group, or carrier battle group.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] There is a view among some military pundits that modern anti-ship weapons systems, such as torpedoes and missiles, or even ballistic missiles with nuclear warheads have made aircraft carriers and carrier groups too vulnerable for modern combat.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carriers are large and long ships, although there is a high degree of variation depending on their intended role and aircraft complement.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The size of the carrier has varied over history and among navies, to cater to the various roles that global climates have demanded from naval aviation.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Regardless of size, the ship itself must house their complement of aircraft, with space for launching, storing, and maintaining them.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Space is also required for the large crew, supplies (food, munitions, fuel, engineering parts), and propulsion.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] US and French aircraft carriers are notable for having nuclear reactors powering their systems and propulsion.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The top of the carrier is the flight deck, where aircraft are launched and recovered.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] On the starboard side of this is the island, where ship navigation from the bridge and air traffic control from flyco are controlled and (in non-nuclear powered vessels), provides the location of the ship's funnel(s).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The *Queen Elizabeth*-class has two island structures; the forward island contains the navigation bridge, while the aft structure houses flyco.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The constraints of constructing a flight deck strongly affect the role of a given carrier, as they influence the weight, type, and configuration of the aircraft that may be launched.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] For example, assisted launch mechanisms are used primarily for heavy aircraft, especially those loaded with air-to-ground weapons.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] CATOBAR is most commonly used on US Navy fleet carriers as it allows the deployment of heavy jets with full load-outs, especially on ground-attack missions.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] STOVL is used by other navies because it is cheaper to operate and still provides good deployment capability for fighter aircraft.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Due to the busy nature of the flight deck, only 20 or so aircraft may be on it at any one time.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] A hangar storage several decks below the flight deck is where most aircraft are kept, and aircraft are taken from the lower storage decks to the flight deck through the use of an elevator.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The hangar is usually quite large and can take up several decks of vertical space.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Munitions are commonly stored on the lower decks because they are highly explosive.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Usually this is below the waterline so that the area can be flooded in case of emergency.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] As "runways at sea", aircraft carriers have a flat-top flight deck, which launches and recovers aircraft.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Aircraft launch forward, into the wind, and are recovered from astern.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Creating such a surface at sea poses constraints on the carrier.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] For example, the size of the vessel is a fundamental limitation on runway length.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] This affects take-off procedure, as a shorter runway length of the deck requires that aircraft accelerate more quickly to gain lift.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] This either requires a thrust boost, a vertical component to its velocity, or a reduced take-off load (to lower mass).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The differing types of deck configuration, as above, influence the structure of the flight deck.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The form of launch assistance a carrier provides is strongly related to the types of aircraft embarked and the design of the carrier itself.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] There are two main philosophies to keep the deck short: add thrust to the aircraft, such as using a Catapult Assisted Take-Off (CATO-); and changing the direction of the airplanes' thrust, as in Vertical and/or Short Take-Off (V/STO-).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] On the recovery side of the flight deck, the adaptation to the aircraft load-out is mirrored.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Non-VTOL or conventional aircraft cannot decelerate on their own, and almost all carriers using them must have arrested-recovery systems (-BAR, e.g.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] CATOBAR or STOBAR) to recover their aircraft.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Aircraft that are landing extend a tailhook that catches on arrestor wires stretched across the deck to bring themselves to a stop in a short distance.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] If the aircraft are VTOL-capable or helicopters, they do not need to decelerate and hence there is no such need.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The arrested-recovery system has used an angled deck since the 1950s because, in case the aircraft does not catch the arresting wire, the short deck allows easier take off by reducing the number of objects between the aircraft and the end of the runway.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] It also has the advantage of separating the recovery operation area from the launch area.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Helicopters and aircraft capable of vertical or short take-off and landing (V/STOL) usually recover by coming abreast of the carrier on the port side and then using their hover capability to move over the flight deck and land vertically without the need for arresting gear.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carriers steam at speed, up to 35 knots (65 km/h; 40 mph) into the wind during flight deck operations to increase wind speed over the deck to a safe minimum.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] This increase in effective wind speed provides a higher launch airspeed for aircraft at the end of the catapult stroke or ski-jump, as well as making recovery safer by reducing the difference between the relative speeds of the aircraft and ship.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since the early 1950s on conventional carriers it has been the practice to recover aircraft at an angle to port of the axial line of the ship.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The primary function of this angled deck is to allow aircraft that miss the arresting wires, referred to as a bolter, to become airborne again without the risk of hitting aircraft parked forward.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The angled deck allows the installation of one or two "waist" catapults in addition to the two bow cats.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] An angled deck also improves launch and recovery cycle flexibility with the option of simultaneous launching and recovery of aircraft.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Conventional ("tailhook") aircraft rely upon a landing signal officer (LSO, radio call sign 'paddles') to monitor the aircraft's approach, visually gauge glideslope, attitude, and airspeed, and transmit that data to the pilot.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Before the angled deck emerged in the 1950s, LSOs used colored paddles to signal corrections to the pilot (hence the nickname).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] From the late 1950s onward, visual landing aids such as the optical landing system have provided information on proper glide slope, but LSOs still transmit voice calls to approaching pilots by radio.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Key personnel involved in the flight deck include the shooters, the handler, and the air boss.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Shooters are naval aviators or naval flight officers and are responsible for launching aircraft.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The handler works just inside the island from the flight deck and is responsible for the movement of aircraft before launching and after recovery.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The captain of the ship spends most of his time one level below primary on the Navigation Bridge.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Below this is the Flag Bridge, designated for the embarked admiral and his staff.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] To facilitate working on the flight deck of a US aircraft carrier, the sailors wear colored shirts that designate their responsibilities.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] There are at least seven different colors worn by flight deck personnel for modern United States Navy carrier air operations.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carrier operations of other nations use similar color schemes.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The superstructure of a carrier (such as the bridge, flight control tower) are concentrated in a relatively small area called an *island*, a feature pioneered on HMS *Hermes* in 1923.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] While the island is usually built on the starboard side of the flight deck, the Japanese aircraft carriers *Akagi* and *Hiryū* had their islands built on the port side.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Very few carriers have been designed or built without an island.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] The *flush deck* configuration proved to have significant drawbacks, primary of which was management of the exhaust from the power plant.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Fumes coming across the deck were a major issue in USS *Langley*.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] In addition, lack of an island meant difficulties managing the flight deck, performing air traffic control, a lack of radar housing placements and problems with navigating and controlling the ship itself.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Another deck structure that can be seen is a ski-jump ramp at the forward end of the flight deck.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] This was first developed to help launch short take off vertical landing (STOVL) aircraft take off at far higher weights than is possible with a vertical or rolling takeoff on flat decks.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Originally developed by the Royal Navy, it since has been adopted by many navies for smaller carriers.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] A ski-jump ramp works by converting some of the forward rolling movement of the aircraft into vertical velocity and is sometimes combined with the aiming of jet thrust partly downward.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] This allows heavily loaded and fueled aircraft a few more precious seconds to attain sufficient air velocity and lift to sustain normal flight.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Without a ski-jump, launching fully-loaded and fueled aircraft such as the Harrier would not be possible on a smaller flat deck ship before either stalling out or crashing directly into the sea.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Although STOVL aircraft are capable of taking off vertically from a spot on the deck, using the ramp and a running start is far more fuel efficient and permits a heavier launch weight.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] As catapults are unnecessary, carriers with this arrangement reduce weight, complexity, and space needed for complex steam or electromagnetic launching equipment.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Vertical landing aircraft also remove the need for arresting cables and related hardware.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Russian, Chinese, and Indian carriers include a ski-jump ramp for launching lightly loaded conventional fighter aircraft but recover using traditional carrier arresting cables and a tailhook on their aircraft.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] For example, the Russian Sukhoi Su-33 is only able to launch from the carrier *Admiral Kuznetsov* with a minimal armament and fuel load.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] Another disadvantage is on mixed flight deck operations where helicopters are also present, such as on a US landing helicopter dock or landing helicopter assault amphibious assault ship.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p01] A ski jump is not included as this would eliminate one or more helicopter landing areas; this flat deck limits the loading of Harriers but is somewhat mitigated by the longer rolling start provided by a long flight deck compared to many STOVL carriers.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The United States operates 11 nuclear-powered, catapult-assisted carriers, with a total combined deck space over twice that of all other nations combined as of 2016.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] China operates one catapult-assisted aircraft carrier and two ski-jump carriers.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The United Kingdom and India each currently operate two ski-jump aircraft carriers, and France operates one nuclear-powered, catapult-assisted carrier.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] Russia deploys one ski-jump carrier, although it has not been operational since 2017.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] In addition, the US operates nine large amphibious assault ships with the capability to launch vertical/short takeoff and landing (V/STOL) aircraft, and China operates four amphibious assault ships of a similar size as helicopter carriers.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] Italy operates two light V/STOL carriers, and both Spain and Iran operate one V/STOL aircraft-carrying assault ship.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] Helicopter carriers are also operated by Japan (4, two converting to operate V/STOL fighters) France (3), Australia (2), Egypt (2), South Korea (2), Thailand (1), Brazil (1) and Iran (1).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] Future aircraft carriers are under construction or planned by China, France, India, Italy, Russia, South Korea, and the US.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Royal Australian Navy operates two *Canberra*-class landing helicopter docks.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The two-ship class, based on the Spanish vessel *Juan Carlos I* and built by Navantia and BAE Systems Australia, represents the largest ships ever built for the Royal Australian Navy.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] HMAS *Canberra* underwent sea trials in late 2013 and was commissioned in 2014.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] Her sister ship, HMAS *Adelaide*, was commissioned in December 2015.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Australian ships retain the ski-ramp from the *Juan Carlos I* design, although the RAN has not acquired carrier-based fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] In December 2017, the Brazilian Navy confirmed the purchase of HMS *Ocean* for (GBP) £84.6 million (equivalent to R$359.5M and US$113.2M) and renamed her *Atlântico*.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The ship was decommissioned from Royal Navy service in March 2018.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Brazilian Navy commissioned the carrier on 29 June 2018 in the United Kingdom.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] After undertaking a period of maintenance in the UK, the ship travelled to its new home port, Rio de Janeiro Navy Arsenal (AMRJ) to be fully operational by 2020.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] Before leaving HMNB Devonport for her new homeport in Rio's AMRJ, *Atlântico* underwent operational sea training under the Royal Navy's Flag Officer Sea Training (FOST) program.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] China has had a long-term plan to operate six large aircraft carriers with two carriers per fleet.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] China is planning a class of eight LHD vessels, the Type 075 (NATO reporting name Yushen-class landing helicopter assault).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] This is a class of amphibious assault ship under construction by the Hudong–Zhonghua Shipbuilding company.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The first ship was commissioned in April 2021.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] China is also planning a modified class of the same concept, the Type 076 landing helicopter dock, that will be equipped with an electromagnetic catapult system and will likely support launching unmanned combat aerial vehicles.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] Egypt signed a contract with French shipbuilder DCNS to buy two *Mistral*-class helicopter carriers for approximately 950 million euros.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The two ships were originally to be sold to Russia, but the deal was cancelled by France due to the Russian invasion of Ukraine in 2014.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 2 June 2016, Egypt received the first of two helicopter carriers acquired in October 2015, the landing helicopter dock *Gamal Abdel Nasser*.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The flag transfer ceremony took place in the presence of Egyptian and French Navies' chiefs of staff, chairman and chief executive officers of both DCNS and STX France, and senior Egyptian and French officials.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 16 September 2016, DCNS delivered the second of two helicopter carriers, the landing helicopter dock *Anwar El Sadat* which also participated in a joint military exercise with the French Navy before arriving at her home port of Alexandria.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The French Navy operates the 42,000-tonne nuclear-powered aircraft carrier, *Charles de Gaulle*.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] Commissioned in 2001, she is the flagship of the French Navy.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The ship carries a complement of Dassault Rafale M and E-2C Hawkeye aircraft, EC725 Caracal and AS532 Cougar helicopters for combat search and rescue, as well as modern electronics and Aster missiles.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] She is a CATOBAR-type carrier that uses two 75 m C13-3 steam catapults of a shorter version of the catapult system installed on the US *Nimitz*-class carriers, one catapult at the bow and one across the front of the landing area.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] In addition, the French Navy operates three *Mistral*-class landing helicopter docks.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] In October 2018, the French Ministry of Defence began an 18-month €40 million study for the replacement of the French aircraft carrier *Charles de Gaulle* sometime after 2030.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] In December 2020, President Macron announced that construction of the next generation carrier would begin in around 2025 with sea trials to start in about 2036.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The carrier is planned to have a displacement of around 75,000 tons and to carry about 32 next-generation fighters, two to three E-2D Advanced Hawkeyes and a yet-to-be-determined number of unmanned carrier air vehicles.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] India has plans for a third carrier, INS *Vishal*, also known as *Indigenous Aircraft Carrier 2 (IAC-2)* with a displacement of over 65,000 tonnes and is planned with a CATOBAR system to launch and recover heavier aircraft.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] India has also issued a request for information (RFI) to procure four Landing helicopter dock displacing 30,000–40,000 tons with a capacity to operate 12 medium lift special ops and two heavy lift helicopters and troops for amphibious operations.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] On February 6, 2025, the Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps (IRGC) accepted the IRIS *Shahid Bagheri*, a 41,978-tonne drone UAV carrier converted from a container ship.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] was launched August 2013 and commissioned March 2015.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] the Japanese defense ministry's position is "We are not creating carrier air wings or carrier air squadrons" similar to the US Navy.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] from land bases; according to the 2020 Japanese Defense Ministry white paper the STOVL model was chosen for the JASDF due the lack of appropriately long runways to support air superiority capability across all of Japanese airspace.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] ships "for cooperation and advice on how to operate the fighter on the deck of the modified ships".
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] , marking 75 years since fixed-wing aircraft operated from a Japanese carrier.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] Portuguese Navy plans, for the second half of 2026, to receive the NRP *D.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] João II*, a platform ship capable of operating aerial, surface and underwater drones, medium helicopters (Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk) and heavy helicopters (EH101 Merlin) helicopters of the Portuguese Air Force.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] One STOBAR carrier: *Admiral Flota Sovetskogo Soyuza Kuznetsov*: 55,000-tonne *Kuznetsov*-class STOBAR aircraft carrier.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] Launched in 1985 as *Tbilisi*, renamed and operational from 1995.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] Without catapults she can launch and recover lightly fueled naval fighters for air defense or anti-ship missions but not heavy conventional bombing strikes.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] Officially designated an aircraft carrying cruiser, she is unique in carrying a heavy cruiser's complement of defensive weapons and large P-700 Granit offensive missiles.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The P-700 systems will be removed in the coming refit to enlarge her below decks aviation facilities as well as upgrading her defensive systems.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The ship has been out of service and in repairs since 2018.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The most recent projection stated that repairs would be completed and the ship transferred back to the Russian Navy sometime in 2024, however this projection has not been met as of July 2025, and no updates have been provided.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Russian government has been considering the potential replacement of *Admiral Kuznetsov* for some time and has considered the Shtorm-class aircraft carrier as a possible option.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] This carrier will be a hybrid of CATOBAR and STOBAR, given the fact that she uses both systems of launching aircraft.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The carrier is expected to cost between $1.8 billion and $5.63 billion.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] As of 2020, the project had not yet been approved and, given the financial costs, it was unclear whether it would be made a priority over other elements of Russian naval modernization.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] A class of 2 LHD, Project 23900 is planned and an official keel laying ceremony for the project happened on 20 July 2020.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] Two *Dokdo*-class 18,860-tonne full deck amphibious assault ships with hospital and well deck and facilities to serve as fleet flagships.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] South Korea had set tentative plans for procuring two light aircraft carriers by 2033, which would help make the ROKN a blue water navy.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] In December 2020, details of South Korea's planned carrier program (CVX) were finalized.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] A vessel of about 40,000 tons is envisaged carrying about 20 F-35B fighters as well as future maritime attack helicopters.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] Service entry had been anticipated in the early 2030s.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] In 2025 the program was cancelled and replaced with a drone carrier program.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] One offshore helicopter support ship: HTMS *Chakri Naruebet* helicopter carrier: 11,400-tonne STOVL carrier based on Spanish *Príncipe de Asturias* design.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The AV-8S Matador/Harrier STOVL fighter wing, mostly inoperable by 1999, was retired from service without replacement in 2006.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] As of 2010, the ship is used for helicopter operations and for disaster relief.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] TCG *Anadolu* is a 27,079-tonne amphibious assault ship (LHD) (outfitted as drone carrier) of the Turkish Navy that can be configured as a 24,660-tonne V/STOL aircraft carrier.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] Construction began on 30 April 2016 by Sedef Shipbuilding Inc. at their Istanbul shipyard.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] TCG *Anadolu* was commissioned with a ceremony on 10 April 2023.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The construction of a sister ship, to be named TCG *Trakya*, is currently being planned by the Turkish Navy.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Sikorsky S-70B Seahawk and the Bell AH-1 SuperCobra are the two main types of helicopters used on TCG *Anadolu*, with the occasional use of CH-47F Chinook helicopters of the Turkish Army during military exercises and operations.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The AH-1W Super Cobras will eventually be complemented and replaced by the TAI T929 ATAK 2.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The jet-powered, low-observable drone Bayraktar MIUS Kızılelma and the MALE UAV Bayraktar TB3 are two UCAVs that are specifically designed and manufactured by Baykar Technologies to be used on TCG *Anadolu*.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The maiden flight of TAI Anka-3 (also part of Project MIUS), a jet-powered, flying wing type UCAV with stealth technology, was successfully completed on 28 December 2023.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 19 November 2024, Baykar Bayraktar TB3 UCAV successfully took-off from the flight deck of TCG *Anadolu* and landed on the ship.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] It was the first time a fixed-wing unmanned aircraft of this size and class had successfully landed on a short-runway landing helicopter dock, without the use of an arresting gear.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 3 January 2024, the Turkish government approved the plan for the design and construction of a larger aircraft carrier, named the *MUGEM*-class.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 15 February 2024, the Design and Projects Office of the Turkish Navy announced that it will be a STOBAR aircraft carrier with an overall length of 285 metres (935 ft), beam of 72 metres (236 ft), draught of 10.1 metres (33 ft), and displacement of 60,000 tons.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] It is to have a combined diesel–electric and gas (CODLAG) propulsion system and a maximum speed of more than 25 knots (29 mph; 46 km/h).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The construction of the first *MUGEM*-class aircraft carrier began on 2 January 2025.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The first *MUGEM*-class aircraft carrier is being built at the Istanbul Naval Shipyard.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] Two 80,600-tonne (est. full load) *Queen Elizabeth*-class STOVL carriers which operate the F-35 Lightning II.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] HMS *Queen Elizabeth* was commissioned in December 2017 and HMS *Prince of Wales* in December 2019.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The current US fleet of *Nimitz*-class carriers will be followed into service (and in some cases replaced) by the *Gerald R.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] It is expected that the ships will be more automated in an effort to reduce the amount of funding required to maintain and operate the vessels.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The main new features are implementation of Electromagnetic Aircraft Launch System (EMALS) (which replaces the old steam catapults) and unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] In terms of future carrier developments, Congress has discussed the possibility of accelerating the phasing-out of one or more *Nimitz*-class carriers, postponing or canceling the procurement of CVN-81 and CVN-82, or modifying the purchase contract.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] Following the deactivation of USS *Enterprise* in December 2012, the US fleet comprised 10 fleet carriers, but that number increased back to 11 with the commissioning of *Gerald R.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The House Armed Services Seapower subcommittee on 24 July 2007, recommended seven or eight new carriers (one every four years).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] However, the debate has deepened over budgeting for the $12–14.5 billion (plus $12 billion for development and research) for the 100,000-tonne *Gerald R.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] Ford*-class carrier (estimated service 2017) compared to the smaller $2 billion 45,000-tonne *America*-class amphibious assault ships, which are able to deploy squadrons of F-35Bs.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The first of this class, USS *America*, is now in active service with another, USS *Tripoli*, and 9 more are planned.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] In a report to Congress in February 2018, the Navy stated it intends to maintain a "12 CVN force" as part of its 30-year acquisition plan.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] A few aircraft carriers have been preserved as museum ships.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] Aircraft carriers are prominently portrayed in a number of Hollywood films including *Midway* (2019) and the carrier USS *Nimitz* is centrally featured in the science fiction film *The Final Countdown* (1980).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The original film version about the Battle at Midway was made in England and titled *Midway* (1976).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] Aircraft carriers are prominently featured in both *Top Gun* and *Top Gun: Maverick* as providing the launch sites and mission operations support for the fighter operations seen in both films.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Japanese aircraft carriers involved in the attack on Pearl Harbor are featured in the 1970 film *Tora!
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] Tora!* as well as the more recent film from 2001 *Pearl Harbor*.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The carrier USS *Ronald Reagan* makes a cameo appearance at the end of the 2012 science fiction film *Battleship*.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] In the 2025 film *Mission: Impossible – The Final Reckoning*, the aircraft carrier USS *George Bush* is featured as delivering its special agent to a submarine rendezvous with the nuclear-powered USS *Ohio* in the Bering Straits by Alaska.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-carrier-p02] The 50-minute documentary titled *City of Steel: Carrier* was released by the Discovery Channel in 2000 covering the final months of building and inspecting the USS *Harry Truman* through its commissioning by President Bill Clinton.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Launching via catapults enables aircraft that typically are only capable of conventional takeoffs, especially heavier aircraft with significant payloads, to perform short takeoffs from the roll distances of light aircraft.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Catapults are usually used on the deck of a ship – such as the flight deck of an aircraft carrier — as a form of assisted takeoff for navalised aircraft, but can also be installed on land-based runways, although this is rare.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Nowadays, jet aircraft can launch from aircraft carriers via either catapults or ski-jump deck, and perform optics-assisted landing onto the same ship with help from decelerative arresting gears.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] When launching, the shuttle is driven forward by force mechanisms within the track system, "hurling out" the aircraft and imparting an additional propulsion on top of the aircraft's own engine thrust to help it accelerate.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Other forms of catapult have been used historically, such as mounting a launching cart holding a seaplane on a long girder-built structure mounted on the deck of a warship or merchant ship, but most catapult systems share a similar sliding track concept.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Different means have been used to propel the catapult, such as weight and derrick, gunpowder, flywheel, compressed air, hydraulic, steam power, and solid fuel rocket boosters.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Since the second half of the 20th century, steam catapults have been the mainstay form of aircraft carrier catapults, especially on the nuclear-powered *Nimitz*-class supercarriers, and is the core component of the catapult-assisted takeoff but arrested recovery (CATOBAR) system.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Into the 21st century, General Atomics has developed an alternating current linear motor-based electromagnetic catapult system called the Electromagnetic Aircraft Launch System (EMALS), which is installed on the United States Navy's new *Gerald R.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Aviation pioneer and Smithsonian Secretary Samuel Langley used a spring-operated catapult to launch his successful flying models and his failed Aerodrome of 1903.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Likewise the Wright Brothers beginning in 1904 used a weight and derrick styled catapult to assist their early aircraft with a takeoff in a limited distance.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] On 31 July 1912, Theodore Gordon Ellyson became the first person to be launched from a U.S.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] The Navy had been perfecting a compressed-air catapult system and mounted it on the Santee Dock in Annapolis, Maryland.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] The first attempt nearly killed Lieutenant Ellyson when the plane left the ramp with its nose pointing upward and it caught a crosswind, pushing the plane into the water.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Ellyson was able to escape from the wreckage unhurt.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Ellyson made history as the Navy's first successful catapult launch, from a stationary coal barge.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] On 5 November 1915, Lieutenant Commander Henry C.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Mustin made the first catapult launch from a ship underway.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] The US Navy experimented with other power sources and models, including catapults that used gunpowder and flywheel variations.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] On 14 December 1924, a Martin MO-1 observation plane flown by Lt.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Hayden was launched from USS *Langley* using a catapult powered by gunpowder.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Following this launch, this method was used aboard both cruisers and battleships.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Up to and during World War II, most catapults on aircraft carriers were hydraulic.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] United States Navy catapults on surface warships, however, were operated with explosive charges similar to those used for 130-millimeter (5-inch) guns.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] They were mostly used for experimental purposes, and their use was entirely discontinued during the latter half of the war.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Many naval vessels apart from aircraft carriers carried float planes, seaplanes or amphibians for reconnaissance and spotting.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] They were catapult-launched and landed on the sea alongside for recovery by crane.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] The first launch off a Royal Navy battlecruiser was from HMAS *Australia* on 8 March 1918.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Subsequently, many Royal Navy ships carried a catapult and from one to four aircraft; battleships or battlecruisers like HMS *Prince of Wales* carried four aircraft and HMS *Rodney* carried two, while smaller warships like the cruiser HMNZS *Leander* carried one.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] The aircraft carried were the Fairey Seafox or Supermarine Walrus.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Some like HMS *Nelson* did not use a catapult, and the aircraft was lowered onto the sea for takeoff.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Some had their aircraft and catapult removed during World War II e.g.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] HMS *Duke of York*, or before (HMS *Ramillies*).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] During World War II a number of ships were fitted with rocket-driven catapults, first the fighter catapult ships of the Royal Navy, then armed merchantmen known as CAM ships from "catapult armed merchantmen".
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] These were used for convoy escort duties to drive off enemy reconnaissance bombers.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] CAM ships carried a Hawker Sea Hurricane 1A, dubbed a "Hurricat" or "Catafighter", and the pilot bailed out unless he could fly to land.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] While imprisoned in Colditz Castle during the war, British prisoners of war planned an escape attempt using a falling bathtub full of heavy rocks and stones as the motive power for a catapult to be used for launching the Colditz Cock glider from the roof of the castle.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Ground-launched V-1s were typically propelled up an inclined launch ramp by an apparatus known as a *Dampferzeuger* ("steam generator").
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Following World War II, the Royal Navy was developing a new catapult system for their fleet of carriers.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Mitchell, RNVR, recommended a steam-based system using a slotted cylinder as an effective and efficient means to launch the next generation of naval aircraft.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] One motive was that the British ships were smaller than their American counterparts and so they had shorter catapult runs, making hydraulic catapults ineffective for launching the new heavier jet fighters.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Trials on HMS *Perseus*, flown by pilots such as Eric "Winkle" Brown, from 1950 showed its effectiveness.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] NATO navies introduced steam catapults based on the British design in the mid-1950s; the U.S.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Navy was also motivated by the need to launch heavy nuclear-armed jet bombers such as the Douglas A-3 Skywarrior and by fatalities caused by flammable hydraulic fluid.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Gunpowder-driven catapults were also contemplated, and would have been powerful enough, but would also have introduced far greater stresses on the airframes and might have been unsuitable for long use.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] At launch, a release bar holds the aircraft in place as steam pressure builds up, then breaks (or "releases"; older models used a pin that sheared), freeing the piston to pull the aircraft along the deck at high speed.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Within about two to four seconds, aircraft velocity by the action of the catapult plus apparent wind speed (ship's speed plus or minus "natural" wind) is sufficient to allow an aircraft to fly away, even after losing one engine.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Nations that have retained large aircraft carriers, i.e., the United States Navy and the French Navy, are still using a CATOBAR (Catapult Assisted Take Off But Arrested Recovery) configuration.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Navy tactical aircraft use catapults to launch with a heavier warload than would otherwise be possible.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Larger planes, such as the E-2 Hawkeye and S-3 Viking, require a catapult shot, since their thrust-to-weight ratio is too low for a conventional rolling takeoff on a carrier deck.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] The protruding angled ramps (Van Velm Bridle Arresters or horns) at the catapult ends on some aircraft carriers were used to catch the bridles (connectors between the catapult shuttle and aircraft fuselage) for reuse.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] There were small ropes that would attach the bridle to the shuttle, which continued down the angled horn to pull the bridle down and away from the aircraft to keep it from damaging the underbelly.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] The bridle would then be caught by nets aside the horn.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Bridles have not been used on U.S. aircraft since the end of the Cold War, and all U.S.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Navy carriers commissioned since then have not had the ramps.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] The last U.S. carrier commissioned with a bridle catcher was USS *Carl Vinson*; starting with USS *Theodore Roosevelt* the ramps were omitted.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] During Refueling and Complex Overhaul refits in the late 1990s–early 2000s, the bridle catchers were removed from the first three *Nimitz*-class aircraft carriers.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Navy operational carrier with the ramps still attached before her inactivation in 2012.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Like her American counterparts, the French aircraft carrier *Charles De Gaulle* is not equipped with bridle catchers because the modern aircraft operated on board use the same launch systems as in US Navy.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Because of this mutual interoperability, American aircraft are also capable of being catapulted from and landing on *Charles De Gaulle*, and conversely, French naval aircraft can use the US Navy carriers' catapults.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] At the time when the Super Étendard was operated on board of the *Charles de Gaulle*, its bridles were used only once, as they were never recovered by bridle catchers.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] The carriers *Clemenceau* and *Foch* were also equipped with bridle catchers, not for the Super Étendards but only to catch and recover the Vought F-8 Crusader's bridles.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] The size and manpower requirements of steam catapults place limits on their capabilities.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] A newer approach is the electromagnetic catapult, such as Electromagnetic Aircraft Launch System (EMALS) developed by General Atomics.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Electromagnetic catapults place less stress on the aircraft and offer more control during the launch by allowing gradual and continual acceleration.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Electromagnetic catapults are also expected to require significantly less maintenance through the use of solid state components.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Linear induction motors have been experimented with before, such as Westinghouse's Electropult system in 1945.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] However, at the beginning of the 21st century, navies again started experimenting with catapults powered by linear induction motors and electromagnets.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Electromagnetic catapult would be more energy efficient on nuclear-powered aircraft carriers and would alleviate some of the dangers posed by using pressurized steam.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] On gas-turbine powered ships, an electromagnetic catapult would eliminate the need for a separate steam boiler for generating catapult steam.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Ford*-class aircraft carriers and PLA Navy's Type 003 aircraft carrier included electromagnetic catapults in their design.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] An alternative approach to solving the problem posed by steam catapults was to integrate a small rocket motor into the catapult shuttle.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] A version of this system known as the C-14 Internal Combustion Catapult Powerplant, powered by jet fuel and compressed air, was developed by Reaction Motors starting in 1954.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] A full-scale mockup of the system was installed at Naval Air Station Lakehurst, and proved capable of generating 70,000,000 ft⋅lbf (95,000,000 J) of energy compared to 66,000,000 ft⋅lbf (89,000,000 J) of the existing C-13, but the system was never fielded.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Originally intended for use on USS *Enterprise* (CVN-65), the ship was redesigned to use conventional C-13 catapults at the behest of Admiral Rickover shortly after launch in 1961 to reduce engineering risk and total cost.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] From 1929, the German Norddeutscher Lloyd-liners SS *Bremen* and *Europa* were fitted with compressed air-driven catapults designed by the *Heinkel Flugzeugwerke* to launch mail-planes.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] These ships served the route between Germany and the United States.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] The aircraft, carrying mail–bags, would be launched as a mail tender while the ship was still many hundreds of miles from its destination, thus speeding mail delivery by about a day.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Initially, Heinkel He 12 aircraft were used before they were replaced by Junkers Ju 46, which were in turn replaced by the Vought V-85G.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] German airline Lufthansa subsequently used dedicated catapult ships SS *Westfalen*, MS *Schwabenland*, *Ostmark* and *Friesenland* to launch larger Dornier Do J *Wal* (whale), Dornier Do 18 and Dornier Do 26 flying boats on the South Atlantic airmail service from Stuttgart, Germany to Natal, Brazil.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] On route proving flights in 1933, and a scheduled service beginning in February 1934, *Wals* flew the trans-ocean stage of the route, between Bathurst, the Gambia in West Africa and Fernando de Noronha, an island group off South America.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] At first, there was a refueling stop in mid-ocean.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] The flying boat would land on the open sea, be winched aboard by a crane, refueled, and then launched by catapult back into the air.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] However, landing on the big ocean swells tended to damage the hull of the flying boats.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] From September 1934, *Lufthansa* had a support ship at each end of the trans-ocean stage, providing radio navigation signals and catapult launchings after carrying aircraft out to sea overnight.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] From April 1935 the *Wals* were launched directly offshore, and flew the entire distance across the ocean.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] This was possible as the flying boats could carry more fuel when they did not have to take off from the water under their own power, and cut the time it took for mail to get from Germany to Brazil from four days down to three.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] From 1936 to 1938, tests including the Blohm & Voss Ha 139 flying boat were conducted on the North Atlantic route to New York.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] *Schwabenland* was also used in an Antarctic expedition in 1938/39 with the main purpose of finding an area for a German whaling station, in which catapult-launched *Wals* surveyed a territory subsequently name after the ship, "Neu-Schwabenland".
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] All of *Lufthansa*'s catapult ships were taken over by the Luftwaffe in 1939 and used as seaplane tenders in World War II along with three catapult ships built for the military.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] After World War II, Supermarine Walrus amphibian aircraft were also briefly operated by a British whaling company, United Whalers.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Operating in the Antarctic, they were launched from the factory ship FF *Balaena*, which had been equipped with an ex-navy aircraft catapult.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] The Chinese, Russian, Indian and currently the Royal Navy have operated conventional aircraft from aircraft carriers without catapults, via the "short take-off but arrested recovery" (STOBAR) system.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] STOBAR carriers use an upward-curved ramp called a ski-jump to assist aircraft takeoff with a positive initial rate of climb, which gives the aircraft's engines more time to accelerate it to the miminum airspeed needed.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] As a result, STOBAR systems are less optimal than CATOBAR systems, but they allow navies who do not have the capabiliity to acquire catapult carriers to still launch fixed-wing aircraft at sea.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] Other navies with aircraft carriers typically operate short take-off and vertical landing (STOVL) aircraft, such as the B variant of the Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning II, the BAE Sea Harrier and the AV-8B Harrier II.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] These aircraft have thrust vectoring and can take off vertically with a light load, or use a ski-jump to assist a conventional takeoff with a heavy load.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/aircraft-catapult] STOVL carriers are less expensive and generally a lot smaller in size than CATOBAR or STOBAR carriers.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] In most circumstances, atmospheric pressure is closely approximated by the hydrostatic pressure caused by the weight of air above the measurement point.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] As elevation increases, there is less overlying atmospheric mass, so atmospheric pressure decreases with increasing elevation.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] Because the atmosphere is thin relative to the Earth's radius – especially the dense atmospheric layer at low altitudes – the Earth's gravitational acceleration as a function of altitude can be approximated as constant and contributes little to this fall-off.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure measures force per unit area, with SI units of pascals (1 pascal = 1 newton per square meter, 1 N/m2).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] A column of air with a cross-sectional area of 1 in2 would have a weight of about 14.7 lbf, resulting in a pressure of 14.7 lbf/in2.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] Atmospheric pressure is caused by the gravitational attraction of the planet on the atmospheric gases above the surface and is a function of the mass of the planet, the radius of the surface, and the amount and composition of the gases and their vertical distribution in the atmosphere.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] It is modified by the planetary rotation and local effects such as wind velocity, density variations due to temperature and variations in composition.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] The *mean sea-level pressure* (MSLP) is the atmospheric pressure at mean sea level.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] This is the atmospheric pressure normally given in weather reports via meteorologists on radio, television, and newspapers or on the Internet.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] The *altimeter setting* in aviation is an atmospheric pressure adjustment.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] In aviation weather reports (METAR), QNH is transmitted around the world in hectopascals or millibars (1 hectopascal = 1 millibar).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] In the United States, Canada, and Japan altimeter setting is reported in inches of mercury (to two decimal places).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] The United States and Canada also report *sea-level pressure* SLP, which is adjusted to sea level by a different method, in the remarks section, not in the internationally transmitted part of the code, in hectopascals or millibars.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] However, in Canada's public weather reports, sea level pressure is instead reported in kilopascals.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] In the US weather code remarks, three digits are all that are transmitted; decimal points and the one or two most significant digits are omitted: 1,013.2 hPa (14.695 psi) is transmitted as 132; 1,000 hPa (100 kPa) is transmitted as 000; 998.7 hPa is transmitted as 987; etc.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] A system transmitting the last three digits transmits the same code (800) for 1080.0 hPa as for 980.0 hPa.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] The highest *sea-level pressure* on Earth occurs in Siberia, where the Siberian High often attains a *sea-level pressure* above 1,050 hPa (15.2 psi; 31 inHg), with record highs close to 1,085 hPa (15.74 psi; 32.0 inHg).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] The lowest measurable *sea-level pressure* is found at the centres of tropical cyclones and tornadoes, with a record low of 870 hPa (12.6 psi; 26 inHg).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] For numerical reasons, atmospheric models such as general circulation models (GCMs) usually predict the nondimensional *logarithm of surface pressure*.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] The average value of surface pressure on Earth is 985 hPa.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] This is in contrast to mean sea-level pressure, which involves the extrapolation of pressure to sea level for locations above or below sea level.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] The average pressure at mean sea level (MSL) in the International Standard Atmosphere (ISA) is 1,013.25 hPa, or 1 atmosphere (atm), or 29.92 inches of mercury.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure (P), mass (m), and acceleration due to gravity (g) are related by P = F/A = (m*g)/A, where A is the surface area.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] Atmospheric pressure is thus proportional to the weight per unit area of the atmospheric mass above that location.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure on Earth varies with the altitude of the surface, so air pressure on mountains is usually lower than air pressure at sea level.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure varies smoothly from the Earth's surface to the top of the mesosphere.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] Although the pressure changes with the weather, NASA has averaged the conditions for all parts of the earth year-round.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] As altitude increases, atmospheric pressure decreases.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] One can calculate the atmospheric pressure at a given altitude.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] Temperature and humidity also affect the atmospheric pressure.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure is proportional to temperature and inversely related to humidity, and both of these are necessary to compute an accurate figure.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] The graph on the rightabove was developed for a temperature of 15 °C and a relative humidity of 0%.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] At low altitudes above sea level, the pressure decreases by about 1.2 kPa (12 hPa) for every 100 meters.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] Atmospheric pressure varies widely on Earth, and differences in pressure are important in studying weather and climate.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] Some variations in pressure are very regular.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] One important source of variation is atmospheric tides.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] Atmospheric tides are strongest in tropical zones, with an amplitude of a few hectopascals, and almost zero in polar areas.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] Tropical tidal variations in pressure consist principally of two superimposed harmonics – a circadian (24 h) cycle and a semi-circadian (12 h) cycle.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] The highest adjusted-to-sea level barometric pressure ever recorded on Earth above 750 meters was 1,084.8 hPa (32.03 inHg; 1.0706 atm), measured in Tosontsengel, Mongolia on 19 December 2001.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] The highest adjusted-to-sea level barometric pressure ever recorded below 750 meters was at Agata, in Evenk Autonomous Okrug, Russia (66°53' N, 93°28' E, elevation: 261 m, 856 ft), on 31 December 1968 of 1,083.8 hPa (32.005 inHg).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] The Dead Sea, the lowest sea surface on Earth, at 430 metres (1,410 ft) below sea level, has a correspondingly high typical atmospheric pressure of 1,065 hPa.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] A below-sea-level surface pressure record of 1,081.8 hPa (31.95 inHg; 1.0677 atm) was set on 21 February 1961.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] The lowest non-tornadic atmospheric pressure ever measured was 870 hPa (26 inHg; 0.86 atm), set on 12 October 1979, during Typhoon Tip in the western Pacific Ocean.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] The measurement was based on an instrumental observation made from a reconnaissance aircraft.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] One atmosphere (101.325 kPa or 14.7 psi) is also the pressure caused by the weight of a column of freshwater of approximately 10.3 m (33.8 ft).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] Thus, a diver 10.3 m under water experiences a pressure of about 2 atmospheres (1 atm of air plus 1 atm of water).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] Conversely, 10.3 m is the maximum height to which water can be raised using suction under standard atmospheric conditions.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] Low pressures, such as natural gas lines, are sometimes specified in inches of water, typically written as *w.c.* (water column) gauge or *w.g.* (inches water) gauge.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] A typical gas-using residential appliance in the US is rated for a maximum of 1⁄2 psi (3.4 kPa; 34 mbar), which is approximately 14 w.g.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] Similar metric units with a wide variety of names and notation based on millimeters, centimeters or meters are now less commonly used.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] Pure water boils at 100 °C (212 °F) at Earth's standard atmospheric pressure.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] The boiling point is the temperature at which the vapour pressure is equal to the atmospheric pressure around the liquid.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] Because of this, the boiling point of liquids is lower at lower pressure and higher at higher pressure.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] Cooking at high elevations, therefore, requires adjustments to recipes or pressure cooking.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] A rough approximation of elevation can be obtained by measuring the temperature at which water boils; in the mid-19th century, this method was used by explorers.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] Conversely, if one wishes to evaporate a liquid at a lower temperature, for example in distillation, the atmospheric pressure may be lowered by using a vacuum pump, as in a rotary evaporator.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] An important application of the knowledge that atmospheric pressure varies directly with altitude was in determining the height of hills and mountains, thanks to reliable pressure measurement devices.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] In 1774, Nevil Maskelyne was confirming Newton's theory of gravitation at and on Schiehallion mountain in Scotland, and he needed to measure elevations on the mountain's sides accurately.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] This event is known as the Schiehallion experiment.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] William Roy, using barometric pressure, was able to confirm Maskelyne's height determinations; the agreement was within one meter (3.28 feet).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/atmospheric-pressure] This method became and continues to be useful for survey work and map making.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] A **clevis fastener** is a two-piece fastener system consisting of a *clevis* and a *clevis pin head*.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] The *clevis* is a U-shaped piece that has holes at the end of the prongs to accept the clevis pin.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] The *clevis pin* is similar to a bolt, but is either partially threaded or unthreaded with a cross-hole for a split pin.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] A *tang* is a piece that is sometimes fitted in the space within the clevis and is held in place by the clevis pin.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] The combination of a simple clevis fitted with a pin is commonly called a *shackle,* although a clevis and pin is only one of the many forms a shackle may take.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] Clevises are used in a wide variety of fasteners used in farming equipment and sailboat rigging, as well as the automotive, aircraft and construction industries.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] They are also widely used to attach control surfaces and other accessories to servo controls in airworthy model aircraft.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] As a part of a fastener, a clevis provides a method of allowing rotation in some axes while restricting rotation in others.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] There are two main types of clevis pins: threaded and unthreaded.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] Unthreaded clevis pins have a domed head at one end and a cross-hole at the other end.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] A cotter pin (US usage) or split pin is used to keep the clevis pin in place.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] Threaded clevis pins have a partially threaded shank on one end and a formed head on the other.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] The formed head has a lip, which acts as a stop when threading the pin into the shackle, and a flattened tab with a cross-hole.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] The flattened tab allows for easy installation of the pin and the cross-hole allows the pin to be moused.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] A bolt can function as a clevis pin, but a bolt is not intended to take the lateral stress that a clevis pin must handle.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] Normal bolts are manufactured to handle tension loads, whereas clevis pins and bolts are designed to withstand shearing forces.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] The shearing strength of a threaded bolt is determined by its inner thread diameter.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] Clevis pins should be closely fitted to the holes in the clevis to limit wear and reduce the failure rate of either the pin or the clevis.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] A twist shackle provides a loop at a right angle to the axis of rotation.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] Older farming implements intended to be pulled by a team of draft animals often require a twist shackle to be hitched.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] A clevis hanger consists of one U-shaped clevis and a second V-shaped clevis with a hole in a flattened section at the base of the V, joined together with a bolt or pin.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] Clevis hangers are used as a pipe attachment providing vertical adjustment for pipes.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] A clevis bracket generally takes the form of a solid metal piece with a flat rectangular base, fitted with holes for bolts or machine screws, and two rounded wings in parallel forming a clevis.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] Commonly used in aircraft and cars, clevis brackets allow mounting of rods to flat surfaces.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] A clevis hook is a hook, with or without a snap lock, with a clevis and bolt or pin at the base.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] The clevis is used to fasten the hook to a bracket or chain.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] A clevis rod end is a folded or machined piece formed into a clevis and fitted with a hole at its base to which a rod is attached.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] In machined pieces, the hole is most often threaded.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] A twin clevis is a solid piece with two clevises directly opposite one another, each fitted with a pin.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/clevis-fastener] Twin clevises are commonly used to join two lengths of chain.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] Its use in designing electronic systems is known as *electronic design automation* (*EDA*).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] In mechanical design it is known as *mechanical design automation* (*MDA*), which includes the process of creating a technical drawing with the use of computer software.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] CAD software for mechanical design uses either vector-based graphics to depict the objects of traditional drafting, or may also produce raster graphics showing the overall appearance of designed objects.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] However, it involves more than just shapes.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] As in the manual drafting of technical and engineering drawings, the output of CAD must convey information, such as materials, processes, dimensions, and tolerances, according to application-specific conventions.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] CAD may be used to design curves and figures in two-dimensional (2D) space; or curves, surfaces, and solids in three-dimensional (3D) space.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] CAD is an important industrial art extensively used in many applications, including automotive, shipbuilding, and aerospace industries, industrial and architectural design (building information modeling), prosthetics, and many more.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] CAD is also widely used to produce computer animation for special effects in movies, advertising and technical manuals, often called DCC digital content creation.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] The modern ubiquity and power of computers means that even perfume bottles and shampoo dispensers are designed using techniques unheard of by engineers of the 1960s.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] Because of its enormous economic importance, CAD has been a major driving force for research in computational geometry, computer graphics (both hardware and software), and discrete differential geometry.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] The design of geometric models for object shapes, in particular, is occasionally called **computer-aided geometric design** (**CAGD**).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] Computer-aided design is one of the many tools used by engineers and designers and is used in many ways depending on the profession of the user and the type of software in question.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] Potential blockage of view corridors and shadow studies are also frequently analyzed through the use of CAD.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] There are several different types of CAD, each requiring the operator to think differently about how to use them and design their virtual components in a different manner.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] Virtually all of CAD tools rely on constraint concepts that are used to define geometric or non-geometric elements of a model.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] There are many producers of the lower-end 2D sketching systems, including a number of free and open-source programs.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] These provide an approach to the drawing process where scale and placement on the drawing sheet can easily be adjusted in the final draft as required, unlike in hand drafting.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] Top-end CAD systems offer the capability to incorporate more organic, aesthetic and ergonomic features into the designs.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] Freeform surface modeling is often combined with solids to allow the designer to create products that fit the human form and visual requirements as well as they interface with the machine.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] Today, CAD systems exist for all the major platforms (Windows, Linux, UNIX and Mac OS X); some packages support multiple platforms.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] Starting with the IBM Drafting System in the mid-1960s, computer-aided design systems began to provide more capabilities than just an ability to reproduce manual drafting with electronic drafting, and the cost-benefit for companies to switch to CAD became apparent.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] The software automated many tasks that are taken for granted from computer systems today, such as automated generation of bills of materials, auto layout in integrated circuits, interference checking, and many others.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] Eventually, CAD provided the designer with the ability to perform engineering calculations.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] During this transition, calculations were still performed either by hand or by those individuals who could run computer programs.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] CAD was a revolutionary change in the engineering industry, where draftsman, designer, and engineer roles that had previously been separate began to merge.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] CAD is an example of the pervasive effect computers were beginning to have on the industry.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] Current computer-aided design software packages range from 2D vector-based drafting systems to 3D solid and surface modelers.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] Modern CAD packages can also frequently allow rotations in three dimensions, allowing viewing of a designed object from any desired angle, even from the inside looking out.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] Some CAD software is capable of dynamic mathematical modeling.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] CAD technology is used in the design of tools and machinery and in the drafting and design of all types of buildings, from small residential types (houses) to the largest commercial and industrial structures (hospitals and factories).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] CAD is mainly used for detailed design of 3D models or 2D drawings of physical components, but it is also used throughout the engineering process from conceptual design and layout of products, through strength and dynamic analysis of assemblies to definition of manufacturing methods of components.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] It can also be used to design objects such as jewelry, furniture, appliances, etc.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] Furthermore, many CAD applications now offer advanced rendering and animation capabilities so engineers can better visualize their product designs.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] 4D BIM is a type of virtual construction engineering simulation incorporating time or schedule-related information for project management.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] CAD has become an especially important technology within the scope of computer-aided technologies, with benefits such as lower product development costs and a greatly shortened design cycle.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] CAD enables designers to layout and develop work on screen, print it out and save it for future editing, saving time on their drawings.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] In the 2000s, some CAD system software vendors shipped their distributions with a dedicated license manager software that controlled how often or how many users can utilize the CAD system.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] It could run either on a local machine (by loading from a local storage device) or a local network fileserver and was usually tied to a specific IP address in latter case.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] CAD software enables engineers and architects to design, inspect and manage engineering projects within an integrated graphical user interface (GUI) on a personal computer system.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] Most applications support solid modeling with boundary representation (B-Rep) and NURBS geometry, and enable the same to be published in a variety of formats.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] Based on market statistics, commercial software from Autodesk, Dassault Systèmes, Siemens PLM Software, and PTC dominate the CAD industry.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/computer-aided-design] The following is a list of major CAD applications, grouped by usage statistics.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Like in a hydraulic cylinder, something forces a piston to move in the desired direction.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] The piston is a disc or cylinder, and the piston rod transfers the force it develops to the object to be moved.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Engineers sometimes prefer to use pneumatics because they are quieter, cleaner, and do not require large amounts of space for fluid storage.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Because the operating fluid is a gas, leakage from a pneumatic cylinder will not drip out and contaminate the surroundings, making pneumatics more desirable where cleanliness is a requirement.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] For example, in the mechanical puppets of the Disney Tiki Room, pneumatics are used to prevent fluid from dripping onto people below the puppets.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Once actuated, compressed air enters into the tube at one end of the piston and imparts force on the piston.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Consequently, the piston becomes displaced.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Pneumatic systems are often found in settings where even rare and brief system failure is unacceptable.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] In such situations, locks can sometimes serve as a safety mechanism in case of loss of air supply (or its pressure falling) and, thus remedy or abate any damage arising in such a situation.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Leakage of air from the input or output reduces the output pressure.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Although pneumatic cylinders will vary in appearance, size and function, they generally fall into one of the specific categories shown below.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] However, there are also numerous other types of pneumatic cylinder available, many of which are designed to fulfill specific and specialized functions.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] A single-acting cylinder (SAC) has one port, which allows compressed air to enter and for the rod to move in one direction only.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] The high pressure of the compressed air causes the rod to extend as the cylinder chamber continues to fill.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] When the compressed air leaves the cylinder through the same port the rod is returned to its original position.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Double-acting cylinders (DAC) use the force of air to move in both extend and retract strokes.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] They have two ports to allow air in, one for outstroke and one for instroke.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Stroke length for this design is not limited, however, the piston rod is more vulnerable to buckling and bending.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Additional calculations should be performed as well.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Telescoping cylinders, also known as telescopic cylinders can be either single or double-acting.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] The telescoping cylinder incorporates a piston rod nested within a series of hollow stages of increasing diameter.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Upon actuation, the piston rod and each succeeding stage "telescopes" out as a segmented piston.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] The main benefit of this design is the allowance for a notably longer stroke than would be achieved with a single-stage cylinder of the same collapsed (retracted) length.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] One cited drawback to telescoping cylinders is the increased potential for piston flexion due to the segmented piston design.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Consequently, telescoping cylinders are primarily utilized in applications where the piston bears minimal side loading.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Rodless cylinders have no rod, only a relatively long piston.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Cable cylinders retain openings at one or both ends, but pass a flexible cable rather than a rod.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] This cable has a smooth plastic jacket for sealing purposes.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] A single cable has to be kept in tension.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Other rodless cylinders close off both ends, coupling the piston either magnetically or mechanically to an actuator that runs along the outside of the cylinder.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] In the magnetic type, the cylinder is thin-walled and of a non-magnetic material, the cylinder is a powerful magnet, and pulls along a magnetic traveller on the outside.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] In the mechanical type, part of the cylinder extends to the outside through a slot cut down the length of the cylinder.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] The slot is then sealed by flexible metal sealing bands on the inside (to prevent gas escape) and outside (to prevent contamination).
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] The piston itself has two end seals, and between them, camming surfaces to "peel off" the seals ahead of the projecting linkage and to replace them behind.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] The interior of the piston, then, is at atmospheric pressure.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] One well-known application of the mechanical type (albeit steam-powered) are the catapults used on many modern aircraft carriers.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Upon job specification, the material may be chosen.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Material range from nickel-plated brass to aluminum, and even steel and stainless steel.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Depending on the level of loads, humidity, temperature, and stroke lengths specified, the appropriate material may be selected.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Air cylinders are available in a variety of sizes and can typically range from a small 2.5 mm (1⁄10 in) air cylinder, which might be used for picking up a small transistor or other electronic component, to 400 mm (16 in) diameter air cylinders which would impart enough force to lift a car.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Some pneumatic cylinders reach 1,000 mm (39 in) in diameter, and are used in place of hydraulic cylinders for special circumstances where leaking hydraulic oil could impose an extreme hazard.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Due to the forces acting on the cylinder, the piston rod is the most stressed component and has to be designed to withstand high amounts of bending, tensile and compressive forces.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Depending on how long the piston rod is, stresses can be calculated differently.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] If the rods length is less than 10 times the diameter, then it may be treated as a rigid body which has compressive or tensile forces acting on it.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] However, if the length of the rod exceeds the 10 times the value of the diameter, then the rod needs to be treated as a column and buckling needs to be calculated as well.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Although the diameter of the piston and the force exerted by a cylinder are related, they are not directly proportional to one another.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Additionally, the typical mathematical relationship between the two assumes that the air supply does not become saturated.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Due to the effective cross sectional area reduced by the area of the piston rod, the instroke force is less than the outstroke force when both are powered pneumatically and by same supply of compressed gas.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] Using the distributed load equation provided the $A_{e}$ can be replaced with area of the piston surface where the pressure is acting on.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] On instroke, the same relationship between force exerted, pressure and *effective cross sectional area* applies as discussed above for outstroke.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] However, since the cross sectional area is less than the piston area the relationship between force, pressure and *radius* is different.
[src:pneumatic-cylinder/pneumatic-cylinder] The calculation isn't more complicated though, since the effective cross sectional area is merely that of the piston surface minus the cross sectional area of the piston rod.
